          "body": "The psalm's decisive argumentative pivot comes in verses 8-10, and it represents one of the Old Testament's most mature theological moves. Asaph does not argue from Israel's innocence. He explicitly asks God not to remember ancestral iniquities (v. 8) and directly confesses 'our sins' (v. 9). His basis for appeal is not merit but name — 'for the glory of Your name,' 'for Your name's sake' (v. 9), and 'Why should the nations say, Where is their God?' (v. 10). This is covenant theology functioning at full strength. The God who bound Himself to Israel by name has staked His own reputation on the outcome of Israel's history. The nations' taunt — 'Where is their God?' — is not merely a social humiliation; it is a theological crisis for the name by which God has chosen to be known. Asaph understands that God's own glory is the strongest possible argument for rescue."
