          "title": "The vow of forever — how lament becomes doxology",
          "body": "Psalm 79 ends in a single verse that transforms everything that preceded it. 'So we Your people and the sheep of Your pasture will give thanks to You forever; to all generations we will tell of Your praise' (v. 13). The shepherd image — 'sheep of Your pasture' — answers the invasion imagery of v. 1 with its deepest counter-claim: however devastated the land, the people still belong to the Shepherd. The 'forever' of threatened anger (v. 5) is displaced by the 'forever' of promised praise (v. 13). The 'all generations' of the vow point past the crisis to a community of testimony that will outlast the Babylonians, the reproach, and the ruins. This is how communal lament functions canonically: it does not deny suffering, but it refuses to let suffering have the final word. The psalm that began in ruin ends in doxology — and the doxology is not cheap; it is purchased through the full, unflinching naming of every dimension of the catastrophe."
